    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the article about Napster, Michael Robinson, a singer of an independent rock group, is quoted as saying: ''Napster has started this Orwellian logic where things aren't really what they seem. Stealing is called 'sharing' or 'sampling,' but in our minds, it's stolen.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the article about Napster, Michael Robinson, a singer of an independent rock group, is quoted as saying: ''Napster has started this Orwellian logic where things aren't really what they seem. Stealing is called 'sharing' or 'sampling,' but in our minds, it's stolen.''</p>
        <p>The true Orwellian language bending in this debate, however, is on the part of the recording industry and other opponents of Napster who continually invoke the notion of the ''artist.'' There is nothing artistic about formulaic songs written by committees, performed by focus-group-approved pop singers and ruthlessly marketed on television and in the press. Nor are any of the participants in this process ''artists.''</p>
        <p>JACK SINGAL  Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
